{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_frenchbulldog_ver04/data/sn83045433/00280764139/1920110501/0009.xml":{"full_text":"WARN AUTOISTS\nTO GO SLOWLY\nHead of Police Traffic\nSquad to Select Most\nDireful.\nNAMES ON HONOR LIST\nTo Be Guests of L. Stoddard\nTaylor, Manager of\nBelasco Theater.\nMotorists, drive carefully!\nThe keen eye of the law. focussed\nby Capt. Albert Headley, chief of the\npolice traffic squad, is wiuching you\nthis week with unusual attention.\nCapt. Headley himself is the\ntraffic expert who this week is selecting\nfor The Washington Herald\nthe fifty most careful motorists in\nWashington.\nThe names of the fifty selected\nfor observance of traffic regulations\nand judgment in driving will appear\nnext Sunday on a roll of honor in\nthe Automotive Section of The\nHerald.\nEach of the fifty also will receive\na letter of congratulation and two\nseats for the comedy. \"When We\nAre Young.\" which Is to be given\nits premiere next week ^t the Belasco\nTheater.\nThe fifty careful motorists will be\nentertained as guests of L. Stoddard\nTaylor, manager of the theater.\nand Henry Hull, who Is appearing\nin the new comedy with a\nwell balanced cast.\nCajJt. Headley began his observations\nyesterday and will continue\nuntil tomorrow midnight. The\ntraffic official is watching auto\ndrivers in all sections of the city.\nWh#?n Headley delivers to T\\ie Herald\nthe names of fifty of the most\ncareful drivers he has seen the!\ntenth careful driving contest of The j\nHerald will be ended and a total j\nof 500 careful autoists, selected dur- i\ning a period of ten weeks, will\nhave been honored for promoting\nsafety first in the streets of Washington.\nREPRISALS TERRORIZE\nIRISH CITY OF TRALEE\nLONDON. Nov. 4 ?Scenes of the\nwildest panic occurred this morn-,\ning In the Irish town of Tralee.\naccording to a correspondent of the i\nLondon Daily Express. The town\nsuffered further reprisals after the\nmilitary forces had left the streets.\nUniformd men emerging from the1\npolice barracks, with hatchets, set'\nfire to the houses of a number of\nknown Sinn Felners.\nTake It from Uncle Eph\nAFTER a man has been married\nfor fifty years he usually j\nkisses his wi(e by th' clock.\nTh' drawback to bein' a native\nof Ohio is, you're apt to be elected\nPresident.\nTfrompaon Feature Senrlee.)\nThe True Frie\nof Every Famih\nEqually effective for parents\nand children It provides a\nsafeguard against all eongks,\ncold* and bronehlal troubles.\nlZ 35c 60c\nHALL'S\nCherry Exmctc\nGel ft at Your Druggist'\nor\nPeople's Drug Stores\na?\nlL\nA Lift\nFor Rooir\n?or anyone who\na position?someone\n?some article?in\npractically everythii\nThe Classifi\nW WASHING\nk\nVananHHHH\n|.r> THE INQUIRING\nKeporter\nHe asks five persons, picked at random,\na question each day.\nTHE QUESTION:\n\"What do you think of the\nelection?\"\nTHE ANSWERS:\nFRANK 8EBRING. clerk of\nthe Police Court t \"I advocated\nthe election of HardiBf, and I\nlow am advocating the formation\nof a traffic court In the j\nDistrict with the same nssur-\nnee of victory that I had in\nconnection with the reault nt\nthe polla.\"\nODELL 9. ftMITH. director of I\nthe Home Defense Lcngaei MI\nam Immensely pleased over the\nontcour of the election. I have\nalways been a Republican* nnd\nwaa particularly anxious to see\nMr. Harding the next President\nof the United States.*\nRICHARD E. WEEDON, actinic\nInspector of the Police Department\ni ?*The Democratic party\nIs a myth. If there ever was\nsuch an organisation In existence\nthere is none now.\"\nIf. R. LEARY( J*- president\nof H. B. Leary Company. Inc.t\n\"With four years of Republican\nadministration before us, I am\nextremely optimistic over the\nbusiness outlook here in Washington\nand \"throughout the\ncountry.\"\nROBERT I. MILLER, attor- j\n4 ney nt law* *The only surprise\nthat came to me on election day\nwas that Hardiag was selected j\nby a majority far greater than\nI anticipated. I visited aeveral\nof the doubtful States during\nOctober, and I was certain that\nthe Republicans were due for a\nstupendous victory, but the actual\nresulta were beyond even\nmy most sanguine expectations.**\nSTORY OFEX-PREMIER'S\nWIFE PRAISED AND\nFLAYEDBY BRITISH\nCONTINUED FROM PAGE ONE.\nadvice of Senator Wadsworth. chairman.\nand Senator Harry New, a\nmember of the Military Affairs Committee,\nbefore deciding definitely\nupon an appointment.\nCol. Theodore Roosevelt has also\nbeen mentioned in connection with\nthe War Department, but it is understood\nto be more likely that he\nwill be made Assistant Secretary of\nWar.\nSenator Weeks, of Massachusetts,\nwith whom Mr. Harding always\nconsulted on naval matters and who\nis himself a graduate of Annapolis,\nis leading as a candidate for trie\nnaval portfolio. It is understood i\ntht the President-elect will talk with\nSenator Poindexter. ranking member\nof the Senate Naval Affairs\nCommittee, before making up his\nmind.\nRoot Tslk Discarded.\nTalk of former Senator Elihu\nRoot as a possible choice for Secretary\nof State has apparently gone\ninto the discard. One reason is that\nFjoot's ideas regarding American\nparticipation in European affairs\nare totally at variance with those\nentertained by Harding.\nFurthermore, it is understood\nthat during his recent visit to Europe\nthe former Secretary of State)\nsent a cablegram giving advice asj\nto the league of nations policy;\nwhich greatly offended the Presi- j\ndential candidate.\nMr. Root is regarded here as being\nso reactionary that the very\nsuggestion of his name would give\ninstant offense to the progressive\nSenators, many of whom unquestionably\nwould refuse to vote for:\nhim on confirmation as a member!\nof the cabinet.\nOtto H. Kahn, of New York, is\ni Line\ni Hunters\nwants anything?\nto fill a position\nfact, you'll find\nag listed on J\ned Page of\nTON HERALD\nTENANTS LOSE\nFIGHT IN COURT\n\nNineteen, However, Appeal\nTo Higher Tribunal for\nJudgment.\nHaving received unfavorable de[\nclalona from the Municipal Court,\nnineteen Waahington tenant, y?.terday\nappealed to the Dl.trlct Supreme\nCourt for judgment. in controversies\nwith their landlord, for\nthe possession of their homes.\nThe Municipal bench awarded to\nSwartlell Rheem and Hensey,\ni po\"e\"'?n of fourteen\napartment. In Fontanet Court. 1400\nllalrmont street northwest, yesterday,\nappeal being filed by thi\nfollowing tenants:\nHerbert L. Chalfont. 110; Lulu I\nWaters, 111; Kenneth Komney 207'\nJames T. Begg, 211; Charles n'\nWoodward. 301; H. E. Hutchins\n302; William S. Webb, 308- On K I\nHealy, 312; Hose B. Gault 314- wu.\nlard R. McConnell, 401; W. H Booze\n504; T. Brent Moore. 509; Jeisie F.\nDawes, 511, and Brooke D. Youngij\nAppeals were also noted by the\nfollowing defendant.:\nMargaret i. Calvin against Lucy\nS Coats, tenant of apartment 41.\nThe Kalorama, 1816 Kalorama road\nnorthwest.\nT. B. Brown Company against\nA\" ?,1,au8hlln, tenant of\n3012 Thirteenth street northwest.\nGardiner and Dent against s. W.\nTuley, .tenant of apartment 12. The\nNorth^npton. 1407 W street northwest.\nMandler Brodt and Company\nagainst Edward C. Snell, tenant of\napartment 2, 131 Eleventh street\nnorthwest.\nJ. Leo Kolb against Mrs. George\nBostwick. tenant of apartment 3,\n1300 Thirty-fifth street northwest.\nFRANCE PROPOSES j\nTAX ON REVOLVERS\nPARIS. Nov. 4.?A tax on revolvers\nis being proposed In France in or-\nder to put a stop to the Increasing\nnumber of aggressions and attacks.\nIn order to purchase a revolver a\nman would require a permit from\nthe police, as the new measure is\napplied, and a receipt for the payment\nof a tax of 110. Any person\nfound with a revolver which had\nnot been bought under the above\nconditions would be severely fined\nor even imprisoned.\nIt Is calculated that about ten\nmillion revolvers are carried in\nFrance by persons of different social\ncategories, from the man who\nwishes to protect his home to the\napaches wttose purpose is different.\nThe tax. at any rate, is expected to\n>et a considerable amount.\nbeing boomed for the Secretaryship J\nof the Treasury.\nMARION, Ohio, Nov. 4.?Sitting In\nthe press house, set amongst the\napple trees and grape vines of hi. I\nback yard. Warren G. Harding. I\nPresident-elect, this evening calmly I\ndiscussed with the correspondent of I\nUniversal Service and his newspaper\nassociates everything except\npolitics. He dumped himself into an\nold-fashioned plush-covered chair,\nlit a stogie and \"talked shop\" He\npaid tribute to Mrs. Harding, who\naided in building up the Marlon\nStar. She had kept books, watched\nthe advertising and spanked the\nnewsboys. because they played I\npranks when the old press balked i\nand refused to function.\nHAVE 1\nHAVE Y(\nIINSPECT THI\nIABSOL\nON FRIDAY, NO\nCommencing at\n\nI' WASI\nAt the Corner of\nSend for Bcaatifnl Booklet\nEach and every lot n\nregardless of yalue,\nRoom 406\nDistrict National Buk Bi\n\"06 G Street N.\nIIIIU Wjuhington, D. C\n\nScenes \"Behind the\nTo Be Shown Hi\nCelebratic\nWmmm\n\nK^Vl\n^;pvSiM>a\n\nI\n^kJ?\nDOLORES\nSpanish movie star, who has bee\ncharge of Armistice Day celcbrat\nbe held here November n, 12 ai\nleading part in the feature film,\nof the attractions.\nDid you ever make a trip thr\nprojecting room, property room, dev\nwill be offered to you at the Americ\nday, a three-day affair to be held h\nUnder direction of Lieut. Charl\non a stage erected at American L\nperiencsd actors forming the cast,\nothers will be made showing the\nmotion pictures. The whole, combin\nart itself, then will be ready for pr<\nDuring the celebration there wi\nentrants from Washington and vicii\npromises to employ in regular motic\nDid you ever make a trip through\na big moving-picture plant?projecting\nroom, property room, devel\noping room, etc.? If not, a chance\nwill be offered you at the American\nLegion's celebration of Armistice\nDay, a three-ply affair to be held\nhere November 11, 12 and 13.\nUnder direction of Lieut. Charles\